{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014cmg6fQKdNwD1cZ9Tm8eZ5","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Cloche Usage\n     2→\n     3→Cloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You define a\n     4→workflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, Cloche copies your project into a Docker\n     5→container, runs the workflow steps (agent prompts and shell scripts), and extracts\n     6→results to a git branch.\n     7→\n     8→## Core Concepts\n     9→\n    10→- **Workflow**: A directed graph of steps connected by named-result wiring.\n    11→- **Step**: A unit of work. Type is inferred: `prompt` = agent step, `run` = script step, `workflow_name` = workflow step (host only).\n    12→- **Result**: A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. `success`, `fail`, `needs-research`). Steps declare their possible results; the engine follows wiring based on the reported result.\n    13→- **Wiring**: Maps `step:result` pairs to the next step. Separate from step definitions.\n    14→- **Terminals**: `done` (success) and `abort` (failure) are built-in terminal targets.\n    15→\n    16→## Workflow DSL\n    17→\n    18→Workflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in `.cloche/`. The first step\n    19→declared is the entry point. Graphs are validated at parse time (all results wired,\n    20→no orphans, entry point exists).\n    21→\n    22→### Minimal Example\n    23→\n    24→```\n    25→workflow \"develop\" {\n    26→  step implement {\n    27→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    28→    results = [success, fail]\n    29→  }\n    30→\n    31→  step test {\n    32→    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    33→    results = [success, fail]\n    34→  }\n    35→\n    36→  implement:success -> test\n    37→  implement:fail -> abort\n    38→  test:success -> done\n    39→  test:fail -> abort\n    40→}\n    41→```\n    42→\n    43→### Step Configuration\n    44→\n    45→| Key | Type | Description |\n    46→|-----|------|-------------|\n    47→| `prompt` | string or `file(\"path\")` | Prompt template. Makes this an agent step. |\n    48→| `run` | string | Shell command. Makes this a script step. |\n    49→| `workflow_name` | string | Container workflow to dispatch. Makes this a workflow step (host only). |\n    50→| `results` | ident list | Declared result names, e.g. `[success, fail, give-up]`. |\n    51→| `max_attempts` | string | Max retries before automatic `give-up` result, e.g. `\"2\"`. |\n    52→| `timeout` | string | Step timeout as Go duration, e.g. `\"30m\"`, `\"2h\"`. Default: 30m. |\n    53→| `agent_command` | string | Agent binary name(s), comma-separated for fallback chains, e.g. `\"claude,gemini\"`. |\n    54→| `agent_args` | string | Override default agent arguments. |\n    55→| `feedback` | string | Set to `\"true\"` to include `.cloche/output/*.log` content in the prompt. |\n    56→| `prompt_step` | string | For workflow steps: which preceding step's output to use as the prompt. |\n    57→\n    58→A step must have exactly one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`.\n    59→\n    60→### The `file()` Function\n    61→\n    62→`file(\"path\")` reads the file at the given path relative to the working directory\n    63→(`/workspace/` in containers) at execution time, not parse time. Use it for prompt\n    64→templates:\n    65→\n    66→```\n    67→prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    68→```\n    69→\n    70→### The `container {}` Block\n    71→\n    72→Can appear at step level or workflow level. Keys are stored with a `container.` prefix.\n    73→\n    74→**Step level** — per-step container config:\n    75→```\n    76→step code {\n    77→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    78→  container {\n    79→    image         = \"custom-agent:v2\"\n    80→    memory        = \"4g\"\n    81→    network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"api.example.com\"]\n    82→  }\n    83→  results = [success, fail]\n    84→}\n    85→```\n    86→\n    87→**Workflow level** — defaults for all steps:\n    88→```\n    89→workflow \"develop\" {\n    90→  container {\n    91→    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n    92→    image         = \"myregistry/myimage:v2\"\n    93→    memory        = \"4g\"\n    94→  }\n    95→  ...\n    96→}\n    97→```\n    98→\n    99→Supported keys: `image`, `memory`, `network_allow`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   100→\n   101→### The `host {}` Block\n   102→\n   103→Declares a workflow as a host workflow. Can appear in any `.cloche` file. Keys are stored\n   104→with a `host.` prefix. Configures agent defaults for agent steps running on the host.\n   105→An empty `host {}` block (no keys) is valid and simply marks the workflow as host-side.\n   106→\n   107→```\n   108→workflow \"main\" {\n   109→  host {\n   110→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   111→  }\n   112→  ...\n   113→}\n   114→```\n   115→\n   116→Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n   117→`agent_args` config keys override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults.\n   118→\n   119→### Wiring Syntax\n   120→\n   121→Connect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n   122→\n   123→```\n   124→implement:success -> test\n   125→implement:fail -> abort\n   126→test:success -> done\n   127→test:fail -> fix\n   128→```\n   129→\n   130→### Wire Output Mappings\n   131→\n   132→Extract values from a step's JSON output and inject as env vars into the target:\n   133→\n   134→```\n   135→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   136→```\n   137→\n   138→Path expressions:\n   139→\n   140→| Expression | Meaning |\n   141→|---|---|\n   142→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   143→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   144→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   145→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   146→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   147→\n   148→If the output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the structure. If it's plain\n   149→text, only bare `output` works.\n   150→\n   151→### Retry Loops\n   152→\n   153→Wire failures back to earlier steps:\n   154→\n   155→```\n   156→test:fail -> fix\n   157→fix:success -> test    // retry the test\n   158→fix:fail -> abort\n   159→```\n   160→\n   161→Use `max_attempts` to cap retries. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n   162→\n   163→```\n   164→step fix {\n   165→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   166→  max_attempts = \"2\"\n   167→  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   168→}\n   169→```\n   170→\n   171→### Parallel Branches (Fanout)\n   172→\n   173→Wire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n   174→\n   175→```\n   176→test:success -> lint\n   177→test:success -> quality\n   178→```\n   179→\n   180→### Collect (Join)\n   181→\n   182→Synchronize parallel branches:\n   183→\n   184→```\n   185→collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   186→collect any(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   187→```\n   188→\n   189→`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n   190→\n   191→### Comments\n   192→\n   193→Line comments with `//`:\n   194→\n   195→```\n   196→// This is a comment\n   197→implement:success -> test  // inline comment\n   198→```\n   199→\n   200→## Result Protocol\n   201→\n   202→Steps report results by printing a marker line to stdout:\n   203→\n   204→```\n   205→CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n   206→```\n   207→\n   208→For example: `CLOCHE_RESULT:success`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:needs-research`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:give-up`.\n   209→\n   210→Rules:\n   211→- The **last** `CLOCHE_RESULT:` line wins if multiple are printed.\n   212→- Marker lines are **stripped** from captured output (not passed to logs or downstream steps).\n   213→- The result name must match one of the step's declared `results`.\n   214→- For script steps with no marker: exit 0 = `success`, exit non-zero = `fail`.\n   215→- For agent steps: if exit non-zero with a marker, the marker result is used. If exit non-zero without a marker, falls back to the next agent in the fallback chain (or returns `fail` if last).\n   216→\n   217→## Prompt Assembly\n   218→\n   219→When an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from these sections (joined by blank lines):\n   220→\n   221→1. **Step template**: The step's `prompt` content (inline string or resolved `file(\"path\")`).\n   222→2. **User request**: Content of `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt` flag), prefixed with `## User Request`.\n   223→3. **Validation output** (opt-in): If `feedback = \"true\"`, reads all `.log` files from `.cloche/output/` and includes them prefixed with `## Validation Output`.\n   224→4. **Result selection**: Lists the step's declared results with instructions to print exactly one `CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>` marker.\n   225→\n   226→The assembled prompt is passed to the agent command via stdin.\n   227→\n   228→## Agent Command Resolution\n   229→\n   230→Priority (highest to lowest):\n   231→1. Step-level `agent_command`\n   232→2. Workflow-level config block (`container { agent_command }` for container workflows, `host { agent_command }` for host workflows)\n   233→3. `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable\n   234→4. Default: `claude`\n   235→\n   236→### Fallback Chains\n   237→\n   238→Comma-separated commands are tried in order:\n   239→\n   240→```\n   241→agent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n   242→```\n   243→\n   244→- **Command not found / failed to start** — try next command\n   245→- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — try next command\n   246→- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — use that result (no fallback)\n   247→- **Exit 0** — use result (no fallback)\n   248→- **All commands fail to start** — step returns an error\n   249→- **Last command crashes without marker** — step returns `fail`\n   250→\n   251→Known agents (e.g. `claude`) get default arguments (`-p --output-format stream-json --verbose --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Unknown agents receive the prompt on stdin with no flags. Override with `agent_args`.\n   252→\n   253→### Agent Setup Guides\n   254→\n   255→For detailed container setup instructions per agent:\n   256→\n   257→- [How to set up Claude Code](agent-setup-claude.md) — session-based auth, no API key needed\n   258→- [How to set up Codex](agent-setup-codex.md) — API key configuration\n   259→\n   260→## Workflow Locations\n   261→\n   262→**Container workflows** (the default) run inside Docker via `cloche-agent`. Steps may\n   263→only be `agent` or `script` type.\n   264→\n   265→**Host workflows** (declared with a `host { }` block) run on the host machine as the\n   266→daemon. Any `.cloche` file can contain host workflows. Steps may be `agent`, `script`,\n   267→or `workflow` type. The `workflow_name` step type dispatches a container workflow run\n   268→and blocks until it completes. Script steps\n   269→execute with their working directory set to the main git worktree, so host-workflow\n   270→fixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n   271→\n   272→A single file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon uses up to three\n   273→host workflow phases for orchestration:\n   274→\n   275→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n   276→|-------|--------------|---------|\n   277→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n   278→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n   279→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n   280→\n   281→Additionally, a **`release-task`** host workflow may be defined. This is not part of the\n   282→automatic orchestration loop — it is invoked on demand (e.g. from the\n   283→web dashboard) to release a stale claimed task back to `open` status. A task is\n   284→considered stale when it has `in_progress` status but no active worker is running for\n   285→it (e.g. after a failed run or daemon restart). The workflow receives `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`.\n   286→\n   287→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a single-workflow\n   288→mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n   289→\n   290→### list-tasks Output Format\n   291→\n   292→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n   293→object:\n   294→\n   295→| Field | Required | Description |\n   296→|-------|----------|-------------|\n   297→| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n   298→| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n   299→| `title` | no | Short summary |\n   300→| `description` | no | Full description |\n   301→| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n   302→\n   303→The daemon picks the first task with status `open`, runs `main` with that task's ID\n   304→set in `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, then runs `finalize` with the outcome. Tasks are\n   305→deduplicated within a timeout window to prevent rapid reassignment of the same task.\n   306→\n   307→### Host Workflow Example\n   308→\n   309→A three-phase host workflow setup:\n   310→\n   311→```\n   312→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   313→  step fetch-tickets {\n   314→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   315→    results = [success, fail]\n   316→  }\n   317→\n   318→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   319→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   320→}\n   321→\n   322→workflow \"main\" {\n   323→  host {\n   324→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   325→  }\n   326→\n   327→  step prepare-prompt {\n   328→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   329→    results = [success, fail]\n   330→  }\n   331→\n   332→  step develop {\n   333→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   334→    results       = [success, fail]\n   335→  }\n   336→\n   337→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   338→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   339→  develop:success        -> done\n   340→  develop:fail           -> done\n   341→}\n   342→\n   343→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   344→  step push-for-review {\n   345→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   346→    results = [success, fail]\n   347→  }\n   348→\n   349→  push-for-review:success -> done\n   350→  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   351→}\n   352→```\n   353→\n   354→The `list-tasks` script writes JSONL to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. The `main` workflow\n   355→receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket. The `finalize`\n   356→workflow receives `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars to decide\n   357→what cleanup to perform.\n   358→\n   359→### Host Step Environment Variables\n   360→\n   361→| Variable | Description |\n   362→|----------|-------------|\n   363→| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory on the host. |\n   364→| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output (for output mappings). |\n   365→| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the output file from the immediately preceding step. |\n   366→| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   367→| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID assigned by the daemon (set for `main` and `finalize` phases). |\n   368→| `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` | Result of the `main` workflow (`succeeded` or `failed`). Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   369→| `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` | Run ID of the completed `main` workflow. Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   370→| Wire-mapped vars | Any env vars declared in wire output mappings. |\n   371→\n   372→### Container Environment Variables\n   373→\n   374→| Variable | Description |\n   375→|----------|-------------|\n   376→| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   377→| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Working directory (set for script steps so `cloche get`/`cloche set` work). |\n   378→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | Passed through from the host if set. |\n   379→| `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` | Overrides the default agent command inside the container. |\n   380→\n   381→## Setting Up Host Workflows\n   382→\n   383→Host workflows are the orchestration layer that ties everything together. When you\n   384→run `cloche init`, a minimal host workflow with just a `main` workflow is generated.\n   385→As your project grows, you can add `list-tasks` and `finalize` workflows to automate\n   386→task discovery and cleanup.\n   387→\n   388→The daemon recognizes three host workflow names and runs them in order:\n   389→\n   390→1. **`list-tasks`** — discover available work\n   391→2. **`main`** — execute the work\n   392→3. **`finalize`** — clean up after the work completes\n   393→\n   394→A fourth optional workflow, **`release-task`**, can be defined for releasing stale\n   395→claimed tasks back to open status. It is not part of the automatic loop — it runs on\n   396→demand when triggered from the web dashboard's Release button.\n   397→\n   398→These host workflows can live in any `.cloche` file(s). Only `main` is required;\n   399→`list-tasks`, `finalize`, and `release-task` are optional.\n   400→\n   401→### `list-tasks` — Discovering Work\n   402→\n   403→The `list-tasks` workflow runs first. Its job is to query your task tracker (issue\n   404→tracker, project board, ticket queue, etc.) and output a list of available tasks.\n   405→\n   406→**When it runs:** The daemon calls `list-tasks` at the start of each orchestration\n   407→loop iteration, before launching any new `main` runs.\n   408→\n   409→**Output format:** The final step must write JSONL (one JSON object per line) to\n   410→`$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. Each line represents a task:\n   411→\n   412→```json\n   413→{\"id\": \"PROJ-42\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Fix login bug\", \"description\": \"Users report...\"}\n   414→{\"id\": \"PROJ-43\", \"status\": \"in-progress\", \"title\": \"Add caching\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   415→{\"id\": \"PROJ-44\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Update docs\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   416→```\n   417→\n   418→The daemon picks the first task with `status: \"open\"` and passes it to `main`.\n   419→Tasks that were recently assigned are deduplicated within a timeout window (default\n   420→5 minutes) to prevent the same task from being picked repeatedly.\n   421→\n   422→**How to configure:** Write a script that queries your task source and outputs JSONL:\n   423→\n   424→```\n   425→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   426→  step fetch-tickets {\n   427→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   428→    results = [success, fail]\n   429→  }\n   430→\n   431→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   432→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   433→}\n   434→```\n   435→\n   436→**If omitted:** The daemon falls back to single-workflow mode — it runs `main`\n   437→once without task assignment. This is fine for simple use cases where you trigger\n   438→runs manually with `cloche run`.\n   439→\n   440→### `main` — Executing Work\n   441→\n   442→The `main` workflow does the actual work. This is the only required host workflow\n   443→and is always generated by `cloche init`.\n   444→\n   445→**When it runs:** After `list-tasks` selects a task (or immediately if `list-tasks`\n   446→is absent). The daemon sets the `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` environment variable from the\n   447→selected task.\n   448→\n   449→**How to configure:** A typical `main` workflow prepares a prompt from the task data,\n   450→then dispatches a container workflow:\n   451→\n   452→```\n   453→workflow \"main\" {\n   454→  host {\n   455→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   456→  }\n   457→\n   458→  step prepare-prompt {\n   459→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   460→    results = [success, fail]\n   461→  }\n   462→\n   463→  step develop {\n   464→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   465→    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n   466→    results       = [success, fail]\n   467→  }\n   468→\n   469→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   470→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   471→  develop:success        -> done\n   472→  develop:fail           -> done\n   473→}\n   474→```\n   475→\n   476→The `workflow_name` step type dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until\n   477→it completes. Use `prompt_step` to specify which preceding step's output should be\n   478→used as the prompt for the container run.\n   479→\n   480→You can add steps before or after the container workflow — for example, a\n   481→`claim-task` step to mark the task as in-progress in your tracker, or a\n   482→`merge-to-main` step to merge the result branch.\n   483→\n   484→### `finalize` — Post-Run Cleanup\n   485→\n   486→The `finalize` workflow handles cleanup after `main` completes. It runs regardless\n   487→of whether `main` succeeded or failed.\n   488→\n   489→**When it runs:** Immediately after `main` finishes (success or failure). The daemon\n   490→sets two additional environment variables:\n   491→\n   492→- `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` — `\"succeeded\"` or `\"failed\"`\n   493→- `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` — the run ID of the completed `main` workflow\n   494→\n   495→**How to configure:** Use the outcome to decide what cleanup to perform:\n   496→\n   497→```\n   498→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   499→  step close-task {\n   500→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/close-task.sh\"\n   501→    results = [success, fail]\n   502→  }\n   503→\n   504→  close-task:success -> done\n   505→  close-task:fail    -> done\n   506→}\n   507→```\n   508→\n   509→A typical `finalize` script checks `$CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and acts accordingly —\n   510→closing the ticket on success, or posting a failure comment for investigation.\n   511→Wiring both results to `done` (not `abort`) ensures the finalize workflow itself\n   512→completes rather than aborting. Note that the overall task status reflects the\n   513→worst outcome of the main and finalize phases — if finalize fails, the task is\n   514→marked as failed even when main succeeded.\n   515→\n   516→**If omitted:** The daemon skips the finalize phase entirely. This is fine if you\n   517→don't need automated cleanup.\n   518→\n   519→### `release-task` — Releasing Stale Claims\n   520→\n   521→The `release-task` workflow handles releasing tasks that are stuck in `in_progress`\n   522→status without an active worker. This happens when a run fails, the daemon restarts,\n   523→or a container is lost. The web dashboard detects these stale tasks and shows a\n   524→**Release** button next to them.\n   525→\n   526→**When it runs:** On demand, when a user clicks Release in the web dashboard. The\n   527→daemon sets `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` to the task being released.\n   528→\n   529→**How to configure:**\n   530→\n   531→```\n   532→workflow \"release-task\" {\n   533→  step release-task {\n   534→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/release-task.sh\"\n   535→    results = [success, fail]\n   536→  }\n   537→\n   538→  release-task:success -> done\n   539→  release-task:fail    -> abort\n   540→}\n   541→```\n   542→\n   543→A typical release script returns the ticket to `open` status and unassigns the owner\n   544→in your task tracker.\n   545→\n   546→**If omitted:** The Release button will not function. Stale tasks must be manually\n   547→unclaimed in your task tracker.\n   548→\n   549→### Putting It All Together\n   550→\n   551→The three-phase model enables fully automated task pipelines:\n   552→\n   553→1. The orchestration loop calls `list-tasks` to find open work\n   554→2. It picks an open task and launches `main` with the task context\n   555→3. `main` prepares a prompt, dispatches a container workflow, and optionally merges results\n   556→4. `finalize` closes the ticket or reports failure\n   557→5. The loop repeats, picking the next open task\n   558→\n   559→Start the loop with `cloche loop` and monitor tasks with `cloche tasks`. The\n   560→`--max` flag controls how many `main` runs execute concurrently.\n   561→\n   562→## Complete Example: Container Workflow with Parallel Validation\n   563→\n   564→```\n   565→workflow \"develop\" {\n   566→  step implement {\n   567→    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n   568→    results = [success, fail]\n   569→  }\n   570→\n   571→  step test {\n   572→    run = \"bundle exec rake test 2>&1\"\n   573→    results = [success, fail]\n   574→  }\n   575→\n   576→  step lint {\n   577→    run = \"bundle exec rubocop 2>&1\"\n   578→    results = [success, fail]\n   579→  }\n   580→\n   581→  step quality {\n   582→    run = \"python3 scripts/quality-check.py 2>&1\"\n   583→    results = [success, fail]\n   584→  }\n   585→\n   586→  step fix {\n   587→    prompt = file(\"prompts/fix.md\")\n   588→    max_attempts = \"2\"\n   589→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   590→  }\n   591→\n   592→  implement:success -> test\n   593→  implement:fail -> abort\n   594→\n   595→  test:success -> lint\n   596→  test:success -> quality\n   597→  test:fail -> fix\n   598→\n   599→  lint:fail -> fix\n   600→  quality:fail -> fix\n   601→  collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   602→\n   603→  fix:success -> test\n   604→  fix:fail -> abort\n   605→  fix:give-up -> abort\n   606→}\n   607→```\n   608→\n   609→## Container Isolation Model\n   610→\n   611→- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the project into `/workspace/`. No bind mounts. Override files from `.cloche/overrides/` are applied on top. `.git/` is included.\n   612→- **Files out**: On completion, the daemon extracts results via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n   613→- **Auth files**: `~/.claude/` and `~/.claude.json` are copied into each container at `/home/agent/` for Claude Code session reuse. Copied (not bind-mounted) so each container gets its own isolated copy.\n   614→- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n   615→- **Cleanup**: Containers are removed after successful runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their container.\n   616→\n   617→Your project directory is never modified by the container.\n   618→\n   619→## CLI Reference\n   620→\n   621→Every subcommand supports `--help` (or `-h`) to show detailed usage, flags, and\n   622→examples. Use `cloche help <command>` for the same output:\n   623→\n   624→```\n   625→cloche --help              # top-level overview\n   626→cloche help run            # detailed help for \"run\"\n   627→cloche run --help          # same as above\n   628→```\n   629→\n   630→### `cloche init`\n   631→\n   632→Scaffold a new Cloche project.\n   633→\n   634→```\n   635→cloche init [--workflow <name>] [--base-image <base>]\n   636→```\n   637→\n   638→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   639→|------|---------|-------------|\n   640→| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   641→| `--base-image <base>` | `cloche-base:latest` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n   642→\n   643→Creates `.cloche/` with workflow file, Dockerfile, `config.toml`, prompt templates,\n   644→host workflows, and prompt generation script. Skips existing files.\n   645→\n   646→### `cloche run`\n   647→\n   648→Launch a workflow run.\n   649→\n   650→```\n   651→cloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--title \"...\"] [--issue ID] [--keep-container]\n   652→```\n   653→\n   654→| Flag | Description |\n   655→|------|-------------|\n   656→| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   657→| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`. |\n   658→| `--title \"...\"` | One-line summary for status display. Auto-generated if omitted. |\n   659→| `--issue ID`, `-i` | Associate a task/issue ID with the run (shown in list output). |\n   660→| `--keep-container` | Keep container on success (failed runs always keep it). |\n   661→\n   662→Must be run from inside a git repository. The daemon auto-rebuilds the Docker image\n   663→when `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes.\n   664→\n   665→### `cloche status`\n   666→\n   667→```\n   668→cloche status <run-id>\n   669→```\n   670→\n   671→Shows run title, type (`host`/`container`), state, active steps, and per-step results.\n   672→\n   673→### `cloche list`\n   674→\n   675→```\n   676→cloche list [flags]\n   677→```\n   678→\n   679→Lists runs for the current project directory. Pass `--all` to show runs across all projects.\n   680→Results can be filtered by state, project, issue, or limited to a fixed number.\n   681→\n   682→| Flag | Description |\n   683→|------|-------------|\n   684→| `--all` | Show runs from all projects (default: current project only). |\n   685→| `--project, -p DIR` | Filter by project directory. |\n   686→| `--state, -s STATE` | Filter by run state (`pending`, `running`, `succeeded`, `failed`, `cancelled`). |\n   687→| `--limit, -n NUM` | Limit the number of results returned. |\n   688→| `--issue, -i ID` | Filter by issue/task ID. |\n   689→\n   690→### `cloche logs`\n   691→\n   692→```\n   693→cloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [-f] [-l <n>]\n   694→```\n   695→\n   696→| Flag | Description |\n   697→|------|-------------|\n   698→| `--step, -s <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n   699→| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Log type filter. |\n   700→| `--follow, -f` | Follow mode: display existing logs then continue streaming new lines as they arrive (like `tail -f`). |\n   701→| `--limit, -l <n>` | Display only the last n lines of output. |\n   702→\n   703→Flags are combinable: `cloche logs run-id -s implement -l 20 -f`\n   704→\n   705→Without `-f`, displays all logs captured to date and exits (even for active runs). With `-f` on an active run, existing logs are sent first, then new output is streamed in real time via gRPC until the run completes.\n   706→\n   707→### `cloche poll`\n   708→\n   709→```\n   710→cloche poll <run-id> [run-id...]\n   711→```\n   712→\n   713→Block until all specified runs finish. Polls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 if all runs succeeded, 1 if any failed or were cancelled.\n   714→\n   715→With a single run ID, prints step-level progress. With multiple run IDs, displays a compact status summary (e.g. `id1: running`) and re-prints whenever a state changes. Use `cloche logs` for detailed output of individual runs.\n   716→\n   717→### `cloche stop`\n   718→\n   719→```\n   720→cloche stop <run-id>\n   721→```\n   722→\n   723→### `cloche delete`\n   724→\n   725→```\n   726→cloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n   727→```\n   728→\n   729→Delete a retained Docker container by container ID or run ID.\n   730→\n   731→### `cloche health`\n   732→\n   733→```\n   734→cloche health\n   735→```\n   736→\n   737→Show per-project pass/fail summary. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP`.\n   738→\n   739→### `cloche workflow`\n   740→\n   741→```\n   742→cloche workflow [--project <dir>]\n   743→cloche workflow <name> [--project <dir>]\n   744→```\n   745→\n   746→List all workflows or render a specific workflow as an ASCII-art graph.\n   747→\n   748→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   749→|------|---------|-------------|\n   750→| `--project <dir>`, `-p` | current directory | Project directory to search for workflows. |\n   751→\n   752→With no arguments, lists all workflows grouped by type (container or host). With a\n   753→workflow name, renders the workflow graph showing step boxes, wiring, and result paths.\n   754→Wires are colorized: green for `success`, red for `fail`/`failed`,\n   755→blue/yellow/orange/magenta for other results. Wires to the same destination are merged\n   756→for readability.\n   757→\n   758→### `cloche validate`\n   759→\n   760→Validate project configuration and workflow definitions.\n   761→\n   762→```\n   763→cloche validate [--project <path>] [--workflow <name>]\n   764→```\n   765→\n   766→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   767→|------|---------|-------------|\n   768→| `--project <path>` | current directory | Project directory to validate. |\n   769→| `--workflow <name>` | _(all)_ | Validate only the named workflow instead of all workflows. |\n   770→\n   771→Checks performed:\n   772→\n   773→- **config.toml** — parses correctly, fields are valid.\n   774→- **Workflow files** — syntax, result wiring completeness, terminal coverage (all paths reach `done`/`abort`), no orphan steps, config key validation.\n   775→- **File references** — prompt `file()` paths resolve to `.cloche/prompts/`, script `run` paths resolve to `.cloche/scripts/`.\n   776→- **Cross-file consistency** — `workflow_name` references in steps resolve to defined workflows.\n   777→\n   778→Exits 0 and prints \"All configuration valid.\" on success. Exits 1 and prints each error with file path on failure.\n   779→\n   780→### `cloche project`\n   781→\n   782→Show project info and config.\n   783→\n   784→```\n   785→cloche project [--name <label>]\n   786→```\n   787→\n   788→By default, looks up the project by the current working directory. Use `--name` to look\n   789→up a project by its registered label instead.\n   790→\n   791→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   792→|------|---------|-------------|\n   793→| `--name <label>` | _(cwd lookup)_ | Look up project by label (e.g. `cloche`) instead of directory. |\n   794→\n   795→Output includes: config settings (active, concurrency, stagger, dedup, stop_on_error,\n   796→evolution), orchestrator loop state (running/stopped/halted), currently active runs,\n   797→and known container and host workflow names. When the loop is halted due to\n   798→`stop_on_error`, the halt error message is displayed.\n   799→\n   800→### `cloche get`\n   801→\n   802→```\n   803→cloche get <key>\n   804→```\n   805→\n   806→Get a value from the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   807→the `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   808→the current working directory. Exits 1 if the key is not found.\n   809→\n   810→### `cloche set`\n   811→\n   812→```\n   813→cloche set <key> <value|->\n   814→```\n   815→\n   816→Set a value in the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   817→the `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   818→the current working directory. Creates the file and directories if they don't exist.\n   819→Pass `-` as the value to read from stdin (trailing newlines are trimmed).\n   820→\n   821→### `cloche tasks`\n   822→\n   823→```\n   824→cloche tasks [--project <dir>]\n   825→```\n   826→\n   827→Show the task pipeline and assignment state for an orchestration loop. Displays\n   828→upcoming/open tasks, which tasks are assigned to which runs, and auto-assignment\n   829→state. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP` (talks to the daemon's web API).\n   830→\n   831→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   832→|------|---------|-------------|\n   833→| `--project <dir>` | current directory name | Project to query tasks for. |\n   834→\n   835→### `cloche loop`\n   836→\n   837→Start, stop, or resume the daemon's orchestration loop. The loop automatically picks up\n   838→tasks from the pipeline and runs them.\n   839→\n   840→```\n   841→cloche loop [--max <n>]\n   842→cloche loop stop\n   843→cloche loop resume\n   844→```\n   845→\n   846→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   847→|------|---------|-------------|\n   848→| `--max <n>` | config value | Maximum concurrent runs. Defaults to the value in `.cloche/config.toml`. |\n   849→\n   850→`cloche loop stop` disables the loop. Running tasks are not cancelled.\n   851→\n   852→`cloche loop resume` clears the halted state after a `stop_on_error` halt, allowing\n   853→the loop to resume picking up new work. See `stop_on_error` in the project config.\n   854→\n   855→### `cloche --version`\n   856→\n   857→Print version information for all Cloche components.\n   858→\n   859→```\n   860→cloche -v\n   861→cloche --version\n   862→```\n   863→\n   864→Displays the CLI version, queries the running daemon for its version (via gRPC),\n   865→and runs `docker run --rm --entrypoint cloche-agent <image> -v` to get the agent\n   866→version from the project's container image. If the daemon is unreachable or the\n   867→image doesn't exist, the corresponding version shows `<unavailable>`. Version\n   868→mismatches between components produce warnings on stderr.\n   869→\n   870→The daemon and agent binaries also support standalone version output:\n   871→\n   872→```\n   873→cloched -v       # prints daemon version\n   874→cloche-agent -v  # prints agent version\n   875→```\n   876→\n   877→### `cloche shutdown`\n   878→\n   879→```\n   880→cloche shutdown\n   881→```\n   882→\n   883→## Project Layout\n   884→\n   885→```\n   886→my-project/\n   887→├── .cloche/\n   888→│   ├── develop.cloche        # Container workflow\n   889→│   ├── host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflows (contain host { } blocks)\n   890→│   ├── Dockerfile            # Container image definition\n   891→│   ├── config.toml           # Project configuration\n   892→│   ├── prompts/              # Prompt templates\n   893→│   │   ├── implement.md\n   894→│   │   ├── fix.md\n   895→│   │   └── update-docs.md\n   896→│   ├── scripts/              # Host-side scripts\n   897→│   ├── overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/\n   898→│   │   └── CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n   899→│   └── <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n   900→│       ├── prompt.txt        # User prompt\n   901→│       ├── context.json      # Shared key-value store (cloche get/set)\n   902→│       ├── output/\n   903→│       │   ├── full.log      # Unified log\n   904→│       │   ├── test.log      # Per-step script output\n   905→│       │   └── llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation\n   906→│       ├── attempt_count/    # Retry counters for max_attempts\n   907→│       └── history.log       # Step execution log\n   908→├── src/                      # Project source (untouched by Cloche)\n   909→└── .git/\n   910→```\n   911→\n   912→## Daemon Configuration\n   913→\n   914→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   915→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   916→| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix://~/.config/cloche/cloche.sock` | Listen address |\n   917→| `CLOCHE_DB` | `~/.config/cloche/cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n   918→| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` or `local` (subprocess, for dev only) |\n   919→| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n   920→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | _(unset)_ | HTTP address for web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n   921→| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | _(auto)_ | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n   922→| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | _(unset)_ | Command for LLM calls (evolution, merge conflicts) |\n   923→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | _(unset)_ | Passed into Docker containers |\n   924→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | _(unset)_ | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n   925→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | _(unset)_ | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n   926→\n   927→### Client Configuration\n   928→\n   929→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   930→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   931→| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix://~/.config/cloche/cloche.sock` | Daemon gRPC address |\n   932→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address |\n   933→\n   934→## Dockerfile Requirements\n   935→\n   936→The container image must have:\n   937→- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n   938→- `git` installed\n   939→- An `agent` user (cloche wraps commands with `chown` + `su agent`)\n   940→- `/workspace` as the working directory\n   941→- Your project's build dependencies and the agent binary (e.g. `claude`)\n   942→\n   943→## Build Commands\n   944→\n   945→```\n   946→make build          # Build all binaries to bin/\n   947→make test           # Run all tests\n   948→make test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\n   949→make lint           # Run go vet\n   950→make proto          # Regenerate gRPC code from protobuf\n   951→make docker-build   # Build the cloche-agent Docker image\n   952→make install        # Build, install to ~/.local/bin/, restart daemon\n   953→make clean          # Remove bin/\n   954→```\n   955→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ddef8504-462d-4fd0-8735-c21e5f29575d","uuid":"ff2d3399-f2ab-47fc-b3fe-0f2650b165ff","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/USAGE.md","content":"# Cloche Usage\n\nCloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You define a\nworkflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, Cloche copies your project into a Docker\ncontainer, runs the workflow steps (agent prompts and shell scripts), and extracts\nresults to a git branch.\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n- **Workflow**: A directed graph of steps connected by named-result wiring.\n- **Step**: A unit of work. Type is inferred: `prompt` = agent step, `run` = script step, `workflow_name` = workflow step (host only).\n- **Result**: A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. `success`, `fail`, `needs-research`). Steps declare their possible results; the engine follows wiring based on the reported result.\n- **Wiring**: Maps `step:result` pairs to the next step. Separate from step definitions.\n- **Terminals**: `done` (success) and `abort` (failure) are built-in terminal targets.\n\n## Workflow DSL\n\nWorkflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in `.cloche/`. The first step\ndeclared is the entry point. Graphs are validated at parse time (all results wired,\nno orphans, entry point exists).\n\n### Minimal Example\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step test {\n    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  implement:success -> test\n  implement:fail -> abort\n  test:success -> done\n  test:fail -> abort\n}\n```\n\n### Step Configuration\n\n| Key | Type | Description |\n|-----|------|-------------|\n| `prompt` | string or `file(\"path\")` | Prompt template. Makes this an agent step. |\n| `run` | string | Shell command. Makes this a script step. |\n| `workflow_name` | string | Container workflow to dispatch. Makes this a workflow step (host only). |\n| `results` | ident list | Declared result names, e.g. `[success, fail, give-up]`. |\n| `max_attempts` | string | Max retries before automatic `give-up` result, e.g. `\"2\"`. |\n| `timeout` | string | Step timeout as Go duration, e.g. `\"30m\"`, `\"2h\"`. Default: 30m. |\n| `agent_command` | string | Agent binary name(s), comma-separated for fallback chains, e.g. `\"claude,gemini\"`. |\n| `agent_args` | string | Override default agent arguments. |\n| `feedback` | string | Set to `\"true\"` to include `.cloche/output/*.log` content in the prompt. |\n| `prompt_step` | string | For workflow steps: which preceding step's output to use as the prompt. |\n\nA step must have exactly one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`.\n\n### The `file()` Function\n\n`file(\"path\")` reads the file at the given path relative to the working directory\n(`/workspace/` in containers) at execution time, not parse time. Use it for prompt\ntemplates:\n\n```\nprompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n```\n\n### The `container {}` Block\n\nCan appear at step level or workflow level. Keys are stored with a `container.` prefix.\n\n**Step level** — per-step container config:\n```\nstep code {\n  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n  container {\n    image         = \"custom-agent:v2\"\n    memory        = \"4g\"\n    network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"api.example.com\"]\n  }\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\n**Workflow level** — defaults for all steps:\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n    image         = \"myregistry/myimage:v2\"\n    memory        = \"4g\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `image`, `memory`, `network_allow`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n\n### The `host {}` Block\n\nDeclares a workflow as a host workflow. Can appear in any `.cloche` file. Keys are stored\nwith a `host.` prefix. Configures agent defaults for agent steps running on the host.\nAn empty `host {}` block (no keys) is valid and simply marks the workflow as host-side.\n\n```\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n`agent_args` config keys override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults.\n\n### Wiring Syntax\n\nConnect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n\n```\nimplement:success -> test\nimplement:fail -> abort\ntest:success -> done\ntest:fail -> fix\n```\n\n### Wire Output Mappings\n\nExtract values from a step's JSON output and inject as env vars into the target:\n\n```\nstep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n```\n\nPath expressions:\n\n| Expression | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n\nIf the output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the structure. If it's plain\ntext, only bare `output` works.\n\n### Retry Loops\n\nWire failures back to earlier steps:\n\n```\ntest:fail -> fix\nfix:success -> test    // retry the test\nfix:fail -> abort\n```\n\nUse `max_attempts` to cap retries. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n\n```\nstep fix {\n  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n  max_attempts = \"2\"\n  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n}\n```\n\n### Parallel Branches (Fanout)\n\nWire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n\n```\ntest:success -> lint\ntest:success -> quality\n```\n\n### Collect (Join)\n\nSynchronize parallel branches:\n\n```\ncollect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\ncollect any(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n```\n\n`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n\n### Comments\n\nLine comments with `//`:\n\n```\n// This is a comment\nimplement:success -> test  // inline comment\n```\n\n## Result Protocol\n\nSteps report results by printing a marker line to stdout:\n\n```\nCLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n```\n\nFor example: `CLOCHE_RESULT:success`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:needs-research`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:give-up`.\n\nRules:\n- The **last** `CLOCHE_RESULT:` line wins if multiple are printed.\n- Marker lines are **stripped** from captured output (not passed to logs or downstream steps).\n- The result name must match one of the step's declared `results`.\n- For script steps with no marker: exit 0 = `success`, exit non-zero = `fail`.\n- For agent steps: if exit non-zero with a marker, the marker result is used. If exit non-zero without a marker, falls back to the next agent in the fallback chain (or returns `fail` if last).\n\n## Prompt Assembly\n\nWhen an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from these sections (joined by blank lines):\n\n1. **Step template**: The step's `prompt` content (inline string or resolved `file(\"path\")`).\n2. **User request**: Content of `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt` flag), prefixed with `## User Request`.\n3. **Validation output** (opt-in): If `feedback = \"true\"`, reads all `.log` files from `.cloche/output/` and includes them prefixed with `## Validation Output`.\n4. **Result selection**: Lists the step's declared results with instructions to print exactly one `CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>` marker.\n\nThe assembled prompt is passed to the agent command via stdin.\n\n## Agent Command Resolution\n\nPriority (highest to lowest):\n1. Step-level `agent_command`\n2. Workflow-level config block (`container { agent_command }` for container workflows, `host { agent_command }` for host workflows)\n3. `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable\n4. Default: `claude`\n\n### Fallback Chains\n\nComma-separated commands are tried in order:\n\n```\nagent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n```\n\n- **Command not found / failed to start** — try next command\n- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — try next command\n- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — use that result (no fallback)\n- **Exit 0** — use result (no fallback)\n- **All commands fail to start** — step returns an error\n- **Last command crashes without marker** — step returns `fail`\n\nKnown agents (e.g. `claude`) get default arguments (`-p --output-format stream-json --verbose --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Unknown agents receive the prompt on stdin with no flags. Override with `agent_args`.\n\n### Agent Setup Guides\n\nFor detailed container setup instructions per agent:\n\n- [How to set up Claude Code](agent-setup-claude.md) — session-based auth, no API key needed\n- [How to set up Codex](agent-setup-codex.md) — API key configuration\n\n## Workflow Locations\n\n**Container workflows** (the default) run inside Docker via `cloche-agent`. Steps may\nonly be `agent` or `script` type.\n\n**Host workflows** (declared with a `host { }` block) run on the host machine as the\ndaemon. Any `.cloche` file can contain host workflows. Steps may be `agent`, `script`,\nor `workflow` type. The `workflow_name` step type dispatches a container workflow run\nand blocks until it completes. Script steps\nexecute with their working directory set to the main git worktree, so host-workflow\nfixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n\nA single file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon uses up to three\nhost workflow phases for orchestration:\n\n| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n|-------|--------------|---------|\n| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n\nAdditionally, a **`release-task`** host workflow may be defined. This is not part of the\nautomatic orchestration loop — it is invoked on demand (e.g. from the\nweb dashboard) to release a stale claimed task back to `open` status. A task is\nconsidered stale when it has `in_progress` status but no active worker is running for\nit (e.g. after a failed run or daemon restart). The workflow receives `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`.\n\nOnly `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a single-workflow\nmode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n\n### list-tasks Output Format\n\nThe `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\nobject:\n\n| Field | Required | Description |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n| `title` | no | Short summary |\n| `description` | no | Full description |\n| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n\nThe daemon picks the first task with status `open`, runs `main` with that task's ID\nset in `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, then runs `finalize` with the outcome. Tasks are\ndeduplicated within a timeout window to prevent rapid reassignment of the same task.\n\n### Host Workflow Example\n\nA three-phase host workflow setup:\n\n```\nworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n  step fetch-tickets {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n}\n\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n\nworkflow \"finalize\" {\n  step push-for-review {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  push-for-review:success -> done\n  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe `list-tasks` script writes JSONL to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. The `main` workflow\nreceives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket. The `finalize`\nworkflow receives `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars to decide\nwhat cleanup to perform.\n\n### Host Step Environment Variables\n\n| Variable | Description |\n|----------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory on the host. |\n| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output (for output mappings). |\n| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the output file from the immediately preceding step. |\n| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID assigned by the daemon (set for `main` and `finalize` phases). |\n| `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` | Result of the `main` workflow (`succeeded` or `failed`). Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n| `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` | Run ID of the completed `main` workflow. Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n| Wire-mapped vars | Any env vars declared in wire output mappings. |\n\n### Container Environment Variables\n\n| Variable | Description |\n|----------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Working directory (set for script steps so `cloche get`/`cloche set` work). |\n| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | Passed through from the host if set. |\n| `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` | Overrides the default agent command inside the container. |\n\n## Setting Up Host Workflows\n\nHost workflows are the orchestration layer that ties everything together. When you\nrun `cloche init`, a minimal host workflow with just a `main` workflow is generated.\nAs your project grows, you can add `list-tasks` and `finalize` workflows to automate\ntask discovery and cleanup.\n\nThe daemon recognizes three host workflow names and runs them in order:\n\n1. **`list-tasks`** — discover available work\n2. **`main`** — execute the work\n3. **`finalize`** — clean up after the work completes\n\nA fourth optional workflow, **`release-task`**, can be defined for releasing stale\nclaimed tasks back to open status. It is not part of the automatic loop — it runs on\ndemand when triggered from the web dashboard's Release button.\n\nThese host workflows can live in any `.cloche` file(s). Only `main` is required;\n`list-tasks`, `finalize`, and `release-task` are optional.\n\n### `list-tasks` — Discovering Work\n\nThe `list-tasks` workflow runs first. Its job is to query your task tracker (issue\ntracker, project board, ticket queue, etc.) and output a list of available tasks.\n\n**When it runs:** The daemon calls `list-tasks` at the start of each orchestration\nloop iteration, before launching any new `main` runs.\n\n**Output format:** The final step must write JSONL (one JSON object per line) to\n`$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. Each line represents a task:\n\n```json\n{\"id\": \"PROJ-42\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Fix login bug\", \"description\": \"Users report...\"}\n{\"id\": \"PROJ-43\", \"status\": \"in-progress\", \"title\": \"Add caching\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n{\"id\": \"PROJ-44\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Update docs\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n```\n\nThe daemon picks the first task with `status: \"open\"` and passes it to `main`.\nTasks that were recently assigned are deduplicated within a timeout window (default\n5 minutes) to prevent the same task from being picked repeatedly.\n\n**How to configure:** Write a script that queries your task source and outputs JSONL:\n\n```\nworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n  step fetch-tickets {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n}\n```\n\n**If omitted:** The daemon falls back to single-workflow mode — it runs `main`\nonce without task assignment. This is fine for simple use cases where you trigger\nruns manually with `cloche run`.\n\n### `main` — Executing Work\n\nThe `main` workflow does the actual work. This is the only required host workflow\nand is always generated by `cloche init`.\n\n**When it runs:** After `list-tasks` selects a task (or immediately if `list-tasks`\nis absent). The daemon sets the `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` environment variable from the\nselected task.\n\n**How to configure:** A typical `main` workflow prepares a prompt from the task data,\nthen dispatches a container workflow:\n\n```\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe `workflow_name` step type dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until\nit completes. Use `prompt_step` to specify which preceding step's output should be\nused as the prompt for the container run.\n\nYou can add steps before or after the container workflow — for example, a\n`claim-task` step to mark the task as in-progress in your tracker, or a\n`merge-to-main` step to merge the result branch.\n\n### `finalize` — Post-Run Cleanup\n\nThe `finalize` workflow handles cleanup after `main` completes. It runs regardless\nof whether `main` succeeded or failed.\n\n**When it runs:** Immediately after `main` finishes (success or failure). The daemon\nsets two additional environment variables:\n\n- `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` — `\"succeeded\"` or `\"failed\"`\n- `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` — the run ID of the completed `main` workflow\n\n**How to configure:** Use the outcome to decide what cleanup to perform:\n\n```\nworkflow \"finalize\" {\n  step close-task {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/close-task.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  close-task:success -> done\n  close-task:fail    -> done\n}\n```\n\nA typical `finalize` script checks `$CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and acts accordingly —\nclosing the ticket on success, or posting a failure comment for investigation.\nWiring both results to `done` (not `abort`) ensures the finalize workflow itself\ncompletes rather than aborting. Note that the overall task status reflects the\nworst outcome of the main and finalize phases — if finalize fails, the task is\nmarked as failed even when main succeeded.\n\n**If omitted:** The daemon skips the finalize phase entirely. This is fine if you\ndon't need automated cleanup.\n\n### `release-task` — Releasing Stale Claims\n\nThe `release-task` workflow handles releasing tasks that are stuck in `in_progress`\nstatus without an active worker. This happens when a run fails, the daemon restarts,\nor a container is lost. The web dashboard detects these stale tasks and shows a\n**Release** button next to them.\n\n**When it runs:** On demand, when a user clicks Release in the web dashboard. The\ndaemon sets `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` to the task being released.\n\n**How to configure:**\n\n```\nworkflow \"release-task\" {\n  step release-task {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/release-task.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  release-task:success -> done\n  release-task:fail    -> abort\n}\n```\n\nA typical release script returns the ticket to `open` status and unassigns the owner\nin your task tracker.\n\n**If omitted:** The Release button will not function. Stale tasks must be manually\nunclaimed in your task tracker.\n\n### Putting It All Together\n\nThe three-phase model enables fully automated task pipelines:\n\n1. The orchestration loop calls `list-tasks` to find open work\n2. It picks an open task and launches `main` with the task context\n3. `main` prepares a prompt, dispatches a container workflow, and optionally merges results\n4. `finalize` closes the ticket or reports failure\n5. The loop repeats, picking the next open task\n\nStart the loop with `cloche loop` and monitor tasks with `cloche tasks`. The\n`--max` flag controls how many `main` runs execute concurrently.\n\n## Complete Example: Container Workflow with Parallel Validation\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step test {\n    run = \"bundle exec rake test 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step lint {\n    run = \"bundle exec rubocop 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step quality {\n    run = \"python3 scripts/quality-check.py 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step fix {\n    prompt = file(\"prompts/fix.md\")\n    max_attempts = \"2\"\n    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n  }\n\n  implement:success -> test\n  implement:fail -> abort\n\n  test:success -> lint\n  test:success -> quality\n  test:fail -> fix\n\n  lint:fail -> fix\n  quality:fail -> fix\n  collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n\n  fix:success -> test\n  fix:fail -> abort\n  fix:give-up -> abort\n}\n```\n\n## Container Isolation Model\n\n- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the project into `/workspace/`. No bind mounts. Override files from `.cloche/overrides/` are applied on top. `.git/` is included.\n- **Files out**: On completion, the daemon extracts results via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n- **Auth files**: `~/.claude/` and `~/.claude.json` are copied into each container at `/home/agent/` for Claude Code session reuse. Copied (not bind-mounted) so each container gets its own isolated copy.\n- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n- **Cleanup**: Containers are removed after successful runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their container.\n\nYour project directory is never modified by the container.\n\n## CLI Reference\n\nEvery subcommand supports `--help` (or `-h`) to show detailed usage, flags, and\nexamples. Use `cloche help <command>` for the same output:\n\n```\ncloche --help              # top-level overview\ncloche help run            # detailed help for \"run\"\ncloche run --help          # same as above\n```\n\n### `cloche init`\n\nScaffold a new Cloche project.\n\n```\ncloche init [--workflow <name>] [--base-image <base>]\n```\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n| `--base-image <base>` | `cloche-base:latest` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n\nCreates `.cloche/` with workflow file, Dockerfile, `config.toml`, prompt templates,\nhost workflows, and prompt generation script. Skips existing files.\n\n### `cloche run`\n\nLaunch a workflow run.\n\n```\ncloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--title \"...\"] [--issue ID] [--keep-container]\n```\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`. |\n| `--title \"...\"` | One-line summary for status display. Auto-generated if omitted. |\n| `--issue ID`, `-i` | Associate a task/issue ID with the run (shown in list output). |\n| `--keep-container` | Keep container on success (failed runs always keep it). |\n\nMust be run from inside a git repository. The daemon auto-rebuilds the Docker image\nwhen `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes.\n\n### `cloche status`\n\n```\ncloche status <run-id>\n```\n\nShows run title, type (`host`/`container`), state, active steps, and per-step results.\n\n### `cloche list`\n\n```\ncloche list [flags]\n```\n\nLists runs for the current project directory. Pass `--all` to show runs across all projects.\nResults can be filtered by state, project, issue, or limited to a fixed number.\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `--all` | Show runs from all projects (default: current project only). |\n| `--project, -p DIR` | Filter by project directory. |\n| `--state, -s STATE` | Filter by run state (`pending`, `running`, `succeeded`, `failed`, `cancelled`). |\n| `--limit, -n NUM` | Limit the number of results returned. |\n| `--issue, -i ID` | Filter by issue/task ID. |\n\n### `cloche logs`\n\n```\ncloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [-f] [-l <n>]\n```\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `--step, -s <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Log type filter. |\n| `--follow, -f` | Follow mode: display existing logs then continue streaming new lines as they arrive (like `tail -f`). |\n| `--limit, -l <n>` | Display only the last n lines of output. |\n\nFlags are combinable: `cloche logs run-id -s implement -l 20 -f`\n\nWithout `-f`, displays all logs captured to date and exits (even for active runs). With `-f` on an active run, existing logs are sent first, then new output is streamed in real time via gRPC until the run completes.\n\n### `cloche poll`\n\n```\ncloche poll <run-id> [run-id...]\n```\n\nBlock until all specified runs finish. Polls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 if all runs succeeded, 1 if any failed or were cancelled.\n\nWith a single run ID, prints step-level progress. With multiple run IDs, displays a compact status summary (e.g. `id1: running`) and re-prints whenever a state changes. Use `cloche logs` for detailed output of individual runs.\n\n### `cloche stop`\n\n```\ncloche stop <run-id>\n```\n\n### `cloche delete`\n\n```\ncloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n```\n\nDelete a retained Docker container by container ID or run ID.\n\n### `cloche health`\n\n```\ncloche health\n```\n\nShow per-project pass/fail summary. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP`.\n\n### `cloche workflow`\n\n```\ncloche workflow [--project <dir>]\ncloche workflow <name> [--project <dir>]\n```\n\nList all workflows or render a specific workflow as an ASCII-art graph.\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--project <dir>`, `-p` | current directory | Project directory to search for workflows. |\n\nWith no arguments, lists all workflows grouped by type (container or host). With a\nworkflow name, renders the workflow graph showing step boxes, wiring, and result paths.\nWires are colorized: green for `success`, red for `fail`/`failed`,\nblue/yellow/orange/magenta for other results. Wires to the same destination are merged\nfor readability.\n\n### `cloche validate`\n\nValidate project configuration and workflow definitions.\n\n```\ncloche validate [--project <path>] [--workflow <name>]\n```\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--project <path>` | current directory | Project directory to validate. |\n| `--workflow <name>` | _(all)_ | Validate only the named workflow instead of all workflows. |\n\nChecks performed:\n\n- **config.toml** — parses correctly, fields are valid.\n- **Workflow files** — syntax, result wiring completeness, terminal coverage (all paths reach `done`/`abort`), no orphan steps, config key validation.\n- **File references** — prompt `file()` paths resolve to `.cloche/prompts/`, script `run` paths resolve to `.cloche/scripts/`.\n- **Cross-file consistency** — `workflow_name` references in steps resolve to defined workflows.\n\nExits 0 and prints \"All configuration valid.\" on success. Exits 1 and prints each error with file path on failure.\n\n### `cloche project`\n\nShow project info and config.\n\n```\ncloche project [--name <label>]\n```\n\nBy default, looks up the project by the current working directory. Use `--name` to look\nup a project by its registered label instead.\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--name <label>` | _(cwd lookup)_ | Look up project by label (e.g. `cloche`) instead of directory. |\n\nOutput includes: config settings (active, concurrency, stagger, dedup, stop_on_error,\nevolution), orchestrator loop state (running/stopped/halted), currently active runs,\nand known container and host workflow names. When the loop is halted due to\n`stop_on_error`, the halt error message is displayed.\n\n### `cloche get`\n\n```\ncloche get <key>\n```\n\nGet a value from the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\nthe `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\nthe current working directory. Exits 1 if the key is not found.\n\n### `cloche set`\n\n```\ncloche set <key> <value|->\n```\n\nSet a value in the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\nthe `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\nthe current working directory. Creates the file and directories if they don't exist.\nPass `-` as the value to read from stdin (trailing newlines are trimmed).\n\n### `cloche tasks`\n\n```\ncloche tasks [--project <dir>]\n```\n\nShow the task pipeline and assignment state for an orchestration loop. Displays\nupcoming/open tasks, which tasks are assigned to which runs, and auto-assignment\nstate. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP` (talks to the daemon's web API).\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--project <dir>` | current directory name | Project to query tasks for. |\n\n### `cloche loop`\n\nStart, stop, or resume the daemon's orchestration loop. The loop automatically picks up\ntasks from the pipeline and runs them.\n\n```\ncloche loop [--max <n>]\ncloche loop stop\ncloche loop resume\n```\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--max <n>` | config value | Maximum concurrent runs. Defaults to the value in `.cloche/config.toml`. |\n\n`cloche loop stop` disables the loop. Running tasks are not cancelled.\n\n`cloche loop resume` clears the halted state after a `stop_on_error` halt, allowing\nthe loop to resume picking up new work. See `stop_on_error` in the project config.\n\n### `cloche --version`\n\nPrint version information for all Cloche components.\n\n```\ncloche -v\ncloche --version\n```\n\nDisplays the CLI version, queries the running daemon for its version (via gRPC),\nand runs `docker run --rm --entrypoint cloche-agent <image> -v` to get the agent\nversion from the project's container image. If the daemon is unreachable or the\nimage doesn't exist, the corresponding version shows `<unavailable>`. Version\nmismatches between components produce warnings on stderr.\n\nThe daemon and agent binaries also support standalone version output:\n\n```\ncloched -v       # prints daemon version\ncloche-agent -v  # prints agent version\n```\n\n### `cloche shutdown`\n\n```\ncloche shutdown\n```\n\n## Project Layout\n\n```\nmy-project/\n├── .cloche/\n│   ├── develop.cloche        # Container workflow\n│   ├── host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflows (contain host { } blocks)\n│   ├── Dockerfile            # Container image definition\n│   ├── config.toml           # Project configuration\n│   ├── prompts/              # Prompt templates\n│   │   ├── implement.md\n│   │   ├── fix.md\n│   │   └── update-docs.md\n│   ├── scripts/              # Host-side scripts\n│   ├── overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/\n│   │   └── CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n│   └── <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n│       ├── prompt.txt        # User prompt\n│       ├── context.json      # Shared key-value store (cloche get/set)\n│       ├── output/\n│       │   ├── full.log      # Unified log\n│       │   ├── test.log      # Per-step script output\n│       │   └── llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation\n│       ├── attempt_count/    # Retry counters for max_attempts\n│       └── history.log       # Step execution log\n├── src/                      # Project source (untouched by Cloche)\n└── .git/\n```\n\n## Daemon Configuration\n\n| Variable | Default | Description |\n|----------|---------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix://~/.config/cloche/cloche.sock` | Listen address |\n| `CLOCHE_DB` | `~/.config/cloche/cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` or `local` (subprocess, for dev only) |\n| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | _(unset)_ | HTTP address for web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | _(auto)_ | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | _(unset)_ | Command for LLM calls (evolution, merge conflicts) |\n| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | _(unset)_ | Passed into Docker containers |\n| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | _(unset)_ | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | _(unset)_ | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n\n### Client Configuration\n\n| Variable | Default | Description |\n|----------|---------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix://~/.config/cloche/cloche.sock` | Daemon gRPC address |\n| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address |\n\n## Dockerfile Requirements\n\nThe container image must have:\n- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n- `git` installed\n- An `agent` user (cloche wraps commands with `chown` + `su agent`)\n- `/workspace` as the working directory\n- Your project's build dependencies and the agent binary (e.g. `claude`)\n\n## Build Commands\n\n```\nmake build          # Build all binaries to bin/\nmake test           # Run all tests\nmake test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\nmake lint           # Run go vet\nmake proto          # Regenerate gRPC code from protobuf\nmake docker-build   # Build the cloche-agent Docker image\nmake install        # Build, install to ~/.local/bin/, restart daemon\nmake clean          # Remove bin/\n```\n","numLines":955,"startLine":1,"totalLines":955}}}
